**The Rapid Viability Test: Fermi Estimation**

**03:18**
I call it the Rapid Viability Test and it's based on a technique called Fermi estimation—the same technique physicists use to make accurate calculations with very limited data. 

**03:29**
Now I'm going to walk you through the framework here, but the complete implementation including the calculation templates, industry benchmarks, and step-by-step worksheets—that's all in the business model validation kit I've created. Let’s walk through the Rapid Viability Test, which has three steps.

**Step 1: Goal Sizing**

**03:45**
Step 1 is Goal Sizing. This is where you define your minimum success criteria. Now most founders and investors will typically target five or ten-year goals, which in a startup results in fictional thinking. 

**03:59**
And that's because it’s impossible to see that far out into the future with a startup, which is why the minimum success criteria flips goal setting on its head and forces you to think deeply, not about how big your idea can get in five or ten years, but rather what’s the smallest outcome that would make your startup worth three years of your life? 

**04:20**
Now why three years? Because that’s usually more than enough time for most founders to hit product-market fit with any idea and you can make much better follow-on growth plans once you hit product-market fit. So setting a tangible minimum success criteria is the first, and I’d argue most important step in this process.

**Step 2: Customer Sizing**

**04:38**
Next, we move on to Customer Sizing. This is where you estimate your annual revenue per customer by thinking of your pricing models. Most founders defer this kind of thinking to later, which is probably the second most costly mistake they make in the startup process. 

**04:55**
As you'll see shortly, pricing is not only part of your product but it determines your customers and your overall market viability. 

**Step 3: Market Sizing**

**05:03**
And the way you test that is in Step 3. This is where you calculate how many customers you'll need to make your model work, and then you verify that your market can indeed support this number. 

**05:15**
Now the magic of Fermi estimation is that unlike financial forecasting, you don't need perfect numbers. You only need to be accurate within an order of magnitude or power of ten, but these simple calculations can still reveal fatal flaws that can save you months of building the wrong thing.

**Applying the Test: Steve and Mary’s Coffee Shop Math**

**05:33**
Let's see it in action with how Mary walks Steve through this test right there at the coffee shop. This is what she asks Steve: "Steve, what would make this VR platform worth spending three years of your life on?" 

**05:50**
And Steve answers: "Well, for one, I'd want to build a real and profitable business." That’s a typical answer that many founders give, but to help him get more concrete, Mary asks him about his fundraising plans. 

**06:01**
"You mentioned fundraising. Can you pull this idea off without any VC funding?" And to that, Steve replies: "I don't know how. This is a massive undertaking and I'll need to hire a big team of people and raise a bunch of money and..." and that's when Mary cuts him off. 

**06:16**
"Okay, in that case your minimum success criteria is no longer set by you, Steve, but your investors. Using these Fermi estimation values, you’ll need to aim for a level three business to earn the attention of an investor at the product-market fit point, which puts your minimum success criteria in the ballpark of building roughly a ten million dollar ARR or annual revenue business by the three-year point."

**06:43**
She then moves on to Step 2 where she starts to size his customers. "How much would software developers pay you monthly for this platform you're envisioning?" 

**06:53**
And Steve replies: "Well, software developers are highly budget-conscious and price-sensitive and I want to attract lots of them and so I was thinking something along the lines of fifty dollars a month." 

**07:03**
And this is where Mary pulls out her napkin sketch and she starts doing the math. "Okay, so that’s six hundred dollars per customer per year. Let’s round that up to a thousand dollars just to make the math simple," to which of course Steve doesn't object. "To hit ten million dollars with a thousand dollar per customer, you would need ten thousand customers."

**The Market Reality Check**

**07:23**
"Do you know how many software developers are currently building these types of VR apps?" Steve drew a complete blank and so they did a quick online search. And the goal again here isn't three-digit precision but a quick ballpark. Their quick search revealed that there were only twenty-two hundred companies and independent software developers at that point in time building these kinds of apps. 

**07:45**
"But this is a new and growing market," Steve protested. And sure, Mary got that, so she said: "Let’s assume this market grows 10x over the next couple of years. And so you will have instead of twenty-two hundred, twenty-two thousand software developers to work with."

**08:00**
"You still have a problem here because no funnel converts at a hundred percent and fifty dollar a month products typically report a one to three percent conversion rate, which means you’d need three hundred thousand at the low end to roughly a million leads to make your business model work. Do you see the problem here?" 

**08:19**
And that’s when Steve really gets it. Even at a twenty or fifty percent conversion rate, this model will never work. The business model is just broken.

**The Pivot: From Developers to Architects**

**08:29**
So Steve's business model just failed the five-minute test, but here’s where the story gets even more powerful. Instead of giving up, Steve asked the right next question: "The model failed because of my pricing. What if I could charge ten or a hundred times more?" 

**08:44**
"That's the right approach, Steve, but how would you get software developers to pay you that much?" And now it was Steve’s turn to interrupt Mary. 

**08:52**
"I wasn't thinking of software developers anymore, but architects. I just finished a small remodeling project and the architect billed me a thousand dollars for a pretty basic 3D rendering. My tool would deliver a much more immersive virtual reality experience and given the size of a typical construction project, I think I could potentially charge architects five thousand dollars per project."

**09:15**
And that's when Mary gets excited. "Wow, yes, that seems completely reasonable. And if we assume that they do ten projects a year, that’s a fifty thousand dollar annual revenue per year, which changes things significantly." 

**09:28**
And this is what the new math looks like: Same ten million dollar goal, but at fifty thousand dollars per customer per year, Steve would only need two hundred architectural firms. 

**09:39**
Now while this is not necessarily easy to pull off, it’s not an impossible model. There are about seventy thousand architectural firms in the US alone. Assuming that only twenty percent do high-end work, that still makes the model highly viable at least on paper.

**10:00**
And the key insight here is that Steve could use the same technology, build the same product or the platform, but instead of targeting price-sensitive software developers, he’d pivot to serve architects who could justify billing their clients for highly immersive virtual reality experiences of their dream homes. 

**10:12**
And that’s the power of this test. It doesn't just tell you if your idea will work or fail—it helps you think through a path to a version that can actually succeed.

